23":"1223","1155":"1155","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1183":"1183","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzAlan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name  <i>Alan</i> (  see  Allen  ), ‘son of  <i>Alan</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]},{"name":"Allen","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Alain</i>, <i>Alein</i> (Old Breton <i>Alan</i>), from a Celtic personal name of great antiquity and obscurity. In England the personal name is now usually spelled <i>Alan</i>, the surname <i>Allen</i>; in Scotland the surname is more often <i>Allan</i>. From 1139 it was common in Scotland, where the surname also derives from Gaelic <i>Ailéne</i>, <i>Ailín</i>, from <i>ail</i> ‘rock’. The present-day frequency of the surname Allen in England and Ireland is partly accounted for by the popularity of the personal name among Breton followers of William the Conqueror, by whom it was imported first to Britain and then to Ireland. Saint Alan(us) was a 5th-century bishop of Quimper, who was a cult figure in medieval Brittany. Another Saint Al(l)an was a Cornish or Breton saint of the 6th century, to whom a church in Cornwall is dedicated.","English: occasionally perhaps from the rare Middle English femaje personal name <i>Aline</i> (Old French <i>Adaline</i>, <i>Aaline</i>), a pet form of ancient Germanic names in <i>Adal-</i>, especially <i>Adalheidis</i> (see   Allis  ).","French: variant of   Allain  , a cognate of 1 above, and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady A FitzAlan was born in 1183, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland. She married Sir Robert Boidh de Boyd in 1223, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1263, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1183–1263":"1183–1263","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1183":"1183","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1183–1263":"1183–1263","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1183":"1183","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1183–1263":"1183–1263","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1183":"1183","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lady A FitzAlan est née en 1183, à Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Écosse. Elle a épousé Sir Robert Boidh de Boyd en 1223, à Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Elle est décédée en 1263, à l’âge de 80 ans."},"de":{"1183–1263":"1183–1263","1155–1240":"1155–1240","1205–1263":"1205–1263","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1155":"1155","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1183":"1183","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Schottland, Unite